The paper deals with epistemic logic programs, which are a popular generalization of Answer Set Programming (ASP) and provide means for reasoning over answer sets within the language. This makes it likely that the paper belongs to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the computational complexity of ELPs and provides a dynamic programming algorithm, which suggests that it could belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) and Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with structural properties of ELPs, which could make it relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of treewidth to bound the number of ASP solver calls, which could make it relevant to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category.
